The moving average, squared error, and average squared error are then computed.

In [4]:
def sqErr(row):
    return (row['Private Construction'] - row['MovAvg'])**2
    
df['MovAvg'] = np.NaN
df['sqErr'] = np.NaN
# Chaging the DataFrame index to DatetimeIndex data type is required for using one of the functions below
df.index = pd.DatetimeIndex(freq='m', start=pd.Timestamp(year=2007, month=8, day=31), periods = len(df['Private Construction']))
#print(len(data),'\n',data)

window = 36
window = window - window % 2
# Compute the moving average in the loop below using a window centered on the data point whose average is eing computed
for i in range(int(window/2),df.shape[0]-int(window/2)):
    df.loc[df.index[i],'MovAvg'] = (0.5*df.iloc[i - int(window/2)]['Private Construction'] + df.iloc[i - int(window/2)+1:i + int(window/2)]['Private Construction'].sum() + 0.5*df.iloc[i + int(window/2)]['Private Construction'])/float(window)

df['sqErr'] = (df['Private Construction'] - df['MovAvg'])**2
# The squared error can eb computed also with the dfHA.apply() method below
# Using dfHS.apply() in this case is unecessary complexity, but it is a good function to know about
#dfHS['sqErr'] = dfHS.apply(sqErr,axis='columns')

# The moving average cannot be applied to all rows and we need to delete those rows because we cannot use them in the analysis
df.dropna(how='any',inplace=True)
df.head()

fig,ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(df['MovAvg'],label='Moving Avg.')
ax.plot(df['Private Construction'],label='Private Construction Spending')
ax.set_xlabel('Year')
ax.set_ylabel('Units of Demand')
ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
print('Average Squared Error per Month: ',sum(df['sqErr'])/len(df))
print(df)

df['R1'] = df['Private Construction'] - df['MovAvg']
df['R1Error'] = abs((df['Private Construction'] - df['R1'])/df['Private Construction'])

The code cell below does these:

  • Computes the remaining residual private construction spending to be explained, R2Private , after subtracting the cyclical component, 𝐶(𝑚) : this is the 𝜖(𝑚) in the model.
  • Computes the error, R2ErrorPrivate , as a percentage of the time series.
  • Computes the mathematical model 'fit', composed of the trend and cyclical components: 𝑇(𝑚)+𝐶(𝑚) .
  • Plots the fit of the model 𝑇(𝑚)+𝐶(𝑚) with the original data, 𝐻(𝑚) .
  • Computes the average absolute error of R2ErrorPrivate of the original time series.
  • Removes the sqErr column because it is no longer needed

df['R2Private'] = df['R1'] - df['C']

def sqErr(row):
    return (row['Public Construction'] - row['MovAvg'])**2

        period = i

The following block of code plots each 12 month cycle, as well as an average of all the cycles.

In [16]:
period = 12
cycleLen = period
numCycles = int(len(df)/cycleLen + 0.5)
cycles = [df.iloc[range(i*period,min((i+1)*period,len(df)))]['R1'] for i in range(numCycles)]
ptsInCycles = [df.iloc[range(i,len(df['R1']),period)]['R1'].tolist() for i in range(period)]
avg = [sum(pts)/len(pts) for pts in ptsInCycles]

fig,ax = plt.subplots()
for i in range(len(cycles)):
    ax.plot(cycles[i].values,label='Cycle '+str(i),c='k')

The code cell below does these:

  • Computes the remaining residual private construction spending to be explained, R2Private , after subtracting the cyclical component, 𝐶(𝑚) : this is the 𝜖(𝑚) in the model.
  • Computes the error, R2ErrorPrivate , as a percentage of the time series.
  • Computes the mathematical model 'fit', composed of the trend and cyclical components: 𝑇(𝑚)+𝐶(𝑚) .
  • Plots the fit of the model 𝑇(𝑚)+𝐶(𝑚) with the original data, 𝐻(𝑚) .
  • Computes the average absolute error of R2ErrorPrivate of the original time series.
  • Removes the sqErr column because it is no longer needed
In [18]:
df['R2Public'] = df['R1'] - df['C']
df['R2ErrorPublic'] = abs(df['R2Public']/df['Public Construction'])
df['fit'] = df['MovAvg'] + df['C']
df.drop(['sqErr'],axis=1,inplace=True)
print('Average Error: ', sum(df['R2ErrorPublic'])/len(df))
print(df)
